Mosque in Temecula wins approval by the planning committee 
The construction of a mosque in Temecula was held after a five-hour, often heated public hearing the unanimous approval by the local planning committee. 
Critics raised before the project to promote both terrorism and traffic jams. 
But according to a statement by the Commission on Wednesday evening, the new religious center meets the local rules and will be an aesthetic eye catching. 
"The project is supported by many good people - Christians, Jews, Baha 'is, and many others," said Hadi Nael, chairman of the Islamic Centre of Temecula Valley on Thursday morning. 
"As Americans, that makes me feel proud." 
"It shows that there is justice." 
"There are only a few opponents," he added. 
"They are just very loud." 
"Living in this valley wonderful people." 
The meeting began at 6: 00 and discussions for and against the construction of the centre lasted almost until midnight, with the voices on both sides, according to the Press-Enterprise were pretty evenly distributed. 
The debate was conducted on the website of the newspaper. 
"There is no longer America," read a comment. 
"It is a different planet of the apes, and the Statue of Liberty is dead in the sand." 
"America is at the end." 
Planned Islamic centres in other parts of the country led to protests, for example, in the vicinity of Ground Zero, the scene of the terrorist attacks on the City of New York on September 11, 2001. 
In the Temecula Valley Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has appealed to non-violence. 
His community with approximately 135 families lived peacefully for years in the River Side County, but they wanted a bigger and better places than the camp, which they have hired a producer for water filtration plants. 
The new, approximately 2300 metres large mosque in the Mediterranean-style is said to have two minarets and around 13m high. 
It is supposed to be on the approximately 17500 m2 large piece of land in the Nicolas Road in the vicinity of the Chaparral High School. 
Opponents of the city council can still appeal against the project. 
